At this lecture we will discuss literature and your experiences related to the recognition and evaluation of opportunities. The assignment is undertaken in groups and your group members will find in due time by clicking "People" and then clicking "Groups for OR Assignment".

Entrepreneurship as a process

- Based on the article by Shane and Venkataraman (2000) how can we understand the process?
- “...we define the field of entrepreneurship as the scholarly examination of how, by whom, and with what effects opportunities to create future goods and services are discovered, evaluated, and exploited (Shane & Venkataraman, 2000; page 218)

Opportunities

- “Entrepreneurial opportunities are those situations in which new goods, services, raw materials, and organizing methods can be introduced...” (Shane & Venkataraman, 2000; page 220).

DEFINITION OF OPPORTUNITY

Based on Baron (2006)

- Baron states three characteristics/qualifications to understand what opportunity refers to.

1. Potential economic value (i.e., the capacity to generate profit)
2. Newness (i.e., some product, service, or technology that did not exist previously),
3. Perceived desirability (e.g., moral and legal acceptability of the new product or service in society).

We often do not fully understand the opportunity from start

“In many cases, this is precisely how new ventures take form; their founders do not initially recognize all aspects of an opportunity. Rather, they notice some aspects and proceed with these. Then, as they obtain experience and information, their view of the opportunity is expanded and refined.” (Baron, 2006: page 111)

HOW YOU UNDERSTAND AND FORMULATE THE PROBLEM

“The way in which people conceptualize a problem strongly influences their likelihood of achieving an original or creative solution.” (Ward, 2004; page 181)

COMING UP WITH OPPORTUNITIES – ANALOGICAL REASONING (WARD 2004)

Analogical reasoning or transfer:

- Applying knowledge from one domain for inspiration in developing ideas in another domain.

Ex →VELCRO®

Ex → Use inspiration from working business models in one industry to transfer it to another industry.

The Role of Prior Knowledge and Experience

- Gabrielsson and Politis (2012) examine how entrepreneurs can be expected to benefit from investments in human capital via work experience, and how this may be influenced by entrepreneurs' preferred way of learning from experience.

_Working experience can consist of:_

1. industry experience
2. business function experience (ex specific experience related to certain functions ex marketing, R & D, finance).

- Learning strategy refers to exploration respectively exploitation.

Key implications

- Besides the advantages from being a specialist with deep work experience, the findings indicate disadvantages and potential barriers to opportunity recognition
- Being a generalist with diverse work experience from different business functions helps with opportunity recognition.
- Learning mindset influence. An exploratory learning mindset facilitates opportunity recognition.
